// Allocate many short-lived arrays in a loop WITHOUT ever calling gcCollect().
// Each iteration builds a fresh 8-element array (~96 bytes) that becomes garbage
// at the end of the block. Over 100000 iterations that is ~9 MiB of cumulative
// allocation, which repeatedly crosses the gc threshold.

say mut i = 0;
while i < 100000 {
    say garbage = [i, i, i, i, i, i, i, i];
    i = i + 1;
}

// The counter proves the program ran to completion through the implicit GCs.
print(i); // expect: 100000

// If automatic collection had never fired, ~9 MiB would still be live here. The
// fact that the heap stayed well under 2 MiB proves auto-GC ran at least once.
print(gcHeapSize() < 2097152); // expect: true
